<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0167 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2012EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Lufthansa-Airbus     02-16 0252</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Lufthansa-Airbus,230</SECOND><HEAD>Deal Could be Worth $3 Billion</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lufthansa German Airlines has signed a contractto purchase as many as 30 commerical aircraft from Airbus Industriein a deal estimated to be worth as much as $3 billion, Airbusofficials announced Thursday.   Lufthansa has agreed to purchase 15 Airbus A340 aircraft, whichare to be delivered between September 1992 and March 1994. Lufthansawill receive both A4340-200s, which seat 222 passengers, and thelarger A340-300s, which have 256-seat cabins.   According to the contract, signed Wednesday, Lufthansa willdecide later on whether to purchase the additional 15 aircraft.   Airbus officials said Lufthansa will use the A340s to replace itsfleet of DC10-30 aircraft. The new jets will enable Lufthansa tooffer more non-stop, long-range routes from Germany to the UnitedStates, South America and the Far East, according to Airbusofficials.   With th Lufthansa order, Airbus now has firm orders, options andcommitments for 110 A340 aircraft.   Lufthansa's order gives another boost to the commercial jetindustry, which is already enjoying a successful year.   Earlier this month, American Airlines signed a 142-plane dealwith McDonnell Douglas Corp. The contract was estimated to be worthas much as $7 billion.   Last year, $48.5 billion dollars worth of new planes wereordered, the highest total ever.   The Lufthansa purchase plan continues a trend predicted byindustry officials, who estimate that the demand to replace agingaircraft could push annual aircraft sales to $450 billion in 1989dollars by the year 2005.</TEXT></DOC>